3406a776-f7e5-4ad9-beff-4cd446bd39d9.0a6bddf3-4935-4f61-9008-6d47f1878f13.description=
Searches the NT Event Log using the supplied search criteria.

Inputs\:
host - The hostname or ip address of the machine you want to search against.
user - Username to use for WMI impersonation on the host for this operation (to be left blank for localhost).
password - Password of the user.
log - The name of the Event Log to search. Example\: Application or System or Security or *.
age - The number of seconds old an event can be to be counted.  Use * for all.
severity - The severity of the event.  Use * for all. Valid values\: error, information, warning, *.
threshold - The value used to determine the response.
eventid - The eventid of the event.
source - The source of the event.
message - The message text of the searched events. If left empty the search will not consider the message.

Responses\:
over threshold - The number of events found was higher than the input parameter threshold or equal to it.
under threshold - The number of events found was lower than the input parameter threshold.
host not found - Host could not be resolved.
Invalid parameters - An unknown Error occurred.

Extra Results\:
count - The total number of events that matched.
logs - The actual logs captured.

Notes\: 
1. The username and password inputs must be blank for localhost and fully qualified usernames must be used for remote hosts.
Example\:
user\: DOMAIN\Administrator
password\: password

2. If a hostname is assigned to the host input, please make sure that the DNS Server you have set is correct, otherwise the hostname will not be resolved.
3406a776-f7e5-4ad9-beff-4cd446bd39d9.33c96d2a-85e8-4385-b986-6a63c3fb0fdf.description=
Changes the status of a Windows service to the requested status.

Inputs\:
host - The hostname or ip address of the target machine.
service - The name of the service to change.
requestedstatus - The requested service status. Valid values are\: running, stopped, paused.
user - The username to use for thread impersonation on the RAS host for this operation (Example\: domain\username). 
password - The password of the user.
startdependants - Start all dependant services. Valid values are\: true, false.
serviceTimeout - The amount of time, in seconds, a single service is allowed to take (it affects the main service and the dependant services).
operationTimeout - The total amount of time, in seconds, the operation is allowed to take for all services combined.

Responses\:
service paused - The service is currently paused.
service running - The service is currently running.
service stopped - The service is currently stopped.
service pending - The service is currently pending.
failure - There was a problem setting the state of the service.

3406a776-f7e5-4ad9-beff-4cd446bd39d9.description=
Checks a dns server for error in the event log that can be resolved by restarting the DNS service and restarts the dns service if any are found.

Inputs\: 
host - A windows dns server.
altuser - The user to authenticate to host as (Example\: domain\username).
altpassword - The password for altuser.

Responses\:
success - DNS service was restarted.
failure - DNS service failed to stop or start.
no restartable events found - DNS was not restarted, since no restartable events were found.
3406a776-f7e5-4ad9-beff-4cd446bd39d9.ea83eb36-19c7-491d-9968-6109a9fe17f5.description=Iterates through a list of values. If the list changes while running, the updates will be appended to the list. Inputs\: list - The list to iterate through. separator - A delimiter that separates elements in the list. Returns\: The current element of the list, if the response is has more Responses\: has more - Another value was in the list, and has been returned. has no more - The iterator has gone fully through the list. This response will only be returned once per iteration through the list, a subsequent call to the Iterator will restart the Iteration through the list. failure - failed to process the list. Note\: Where the iterator is in the list is tracked by each step's unique id. Therefore you can iterate on the same list from multiple steps simultaneously. WARNING\: Any step that will use the results of this Iterator operation will, by default, attempt to assign that step's inputs from a flow variable. If this is left checked, then the first element of the iterator will be used for every cycle of iteration..
